# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: api-gateway-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] A server that acts as an API front-end receives API requests, enforces throttling and security policies, passes requests to the back-end service and then passes the response back to the requester.
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] A gateway often includes a transformation engine to orchestrate and modify the requests and responses on the fly.
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] A gateway can also provide functions such as collecting analytics data and providing caching.
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] The gateway can provide the functionality to support authentication, authorization, security, audit and regulatory compliance.
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] Functionality to monitor API usage and load (overall hits, completed transactions, number of data objects returned, amount of compute time and other internal resources consumed, the volume of data transferred).
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] This can include real-time API monitoring with alerts being raised directly or via a higher-level network management system, for instance, if the load on an API has become too great, as well as functionality to analyze historical data, such as transaction logs, to detect usage trends.
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] Functionality can also be provided to create synthetic transactions that can be used to test the performance and behavior of API endpoints.
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] The API provider can use the information gathered by the reporting and analytics functionality to optimize the API offering within an organization's overall continuous improvement process and define software Service-Level Agreements for APIs.
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] Functionality to support charging for access to commercial APIs.
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] This functionality can include support for setting up pricing rules based on usage, load and functionality, issuing invoices, and collecting payments, including multiple types of credit card payments.
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] Several industry analysts have observed that the market size for API management solutions has been growing rapidly since the early 2010s.
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] Gartner estimated the market size for API management to be $70 million in 2013, growing at 40% a year.
[src:api-gateway-security/api-management] According to Forrester Research, in the US alone, annual spend on API management was $140 million in 2014, expected to grow to $660 million by 2020, with total global sales predicted to exceed a billion dollars by that year.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:api-gateway-security/application-programming-interface] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Generally, the OAuth protocol provides a way for resource owners to provide a client application with secure delegated access to server resources.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] It specifies a process for resource owners to authorize third-party access to their server resources without providing credentials.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Designed specifically to work with Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), OAuth essentially allows access tokens to be issued to third-party clients by an authorization server, with the approval of the resource owner.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] The third party then uses the access token to access the protected resources hosted by the resource server.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth began in November 2006 when Blaine Cook was developing an OpenID implementation for Twitter.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Meanwhile, Ma.gnolia needed a solution to allow its members with OpenIDs to authorize Mac OS X Dashboard widgets to access their service.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Cook, Chris Messina and Larry Halff from Magnolia met with David Recordon to discuss using OpenID with the Twitter and Magnolia APIs to delegate authentication.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] They concluded that there were no open standards for API access delegation.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] The OAuth discussion group was created in April 2007, for a small group of implementers to write the draft proposal for an open protocol.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] DeWitt Clinton from Google learned of the OAuth project, and expressed his interest in supporting the effort.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] In July 2007, the team drafted an initial specification.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Eran Hammer joined and coordinated the many OAuth contributions creating a more formal specification.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] On 3 October 2007, the OAuth Core 1.0 final draft was released.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] At the 73rd Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) meeting in Minneapolis in November 2008, an OAuth BoF was held to discuss bringing the protocol into the IETF for further standardization work.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] The event was well attended and there was wide support for formally chartering an OAuth working group within the IETF.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] The OAuth 1.0 protocol was published as RFC 5849, an informational Request for Comments, in April 2010.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Since 31 August 2010, all third party Twitter applications have been required to use OAuth.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] The OAuth 2.0 framework was published considering additional use cases and extensibility requirements gathered from the wider IETF community.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Albeit being built on the OAuth 1.0 deployment experience, OAuth 2.0 is not backwards compatible with OAuth 1.0.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth 2.0 was published as RFC 6749 and the Bearer Token Usage specification as RFC 6750, both standards track Requests for Comments, in October 2012.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] As of November 2024, the OAuth 2.1 Authorization Framework draft is a work in progress.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] It consolidates the functionality in RFCs OAuth 2.0, OAuth 2.0 for Native Apps, Proof Key for Code Exchange, OAuth 2.0 for Browser-Based Apps, OAuth Security Best Current, and Bearer Token Usage.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] On 23 April 2009, a session fixation security flaw in the 1.0 protocol was announced.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] It affects the OAuth authorization flow (also known as "3-legged OAuth") in OAuth Core 1.0 Section 6.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Version 1.0a of the OAuth Core protocol was issued to address this issue.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] In January 2013, the Internet Engineering Task Force published a threat model for OAuth 2.0.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Among the threats outlined is one called "Open Redirector"; in early 2014, a variant of this was described under the name "Covert Redirect" by Wang Jing.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth 2.0 has been analyzed using formal web protocol analysis.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] This analysis revealed that in setups with multiple authorization servers, one of which is behaving maliciously, clients can become confused about the authorization server to use and may forward secrets to the malicious authorization server (AS Mix-Up Attack).
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] This prompted the creation of a new best current practice internet draft that sets out to define a new security standard for OAuth 2.0.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Assuming a fix against the AS Mix-Up Attack in place, the security of OAuth 2.0 has been proven under strong attacker models using formal analysis.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] One implementation of OAuth 2.0 with numerous security flaws has been exposed.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] In April and May 2017, about one million users of Gmail (less than 0.1% of users as of May 2017) were targeted by an OAuth-based phishing attack, receiving an email purporting to be from a colleague, employer or friend wanting to share a document on Google Docs.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Those who clicked on the link within the email were directed to sign in and allow a potentially malicious third-party program called "Google Apps" to access their "email account, contacts and online documents".
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Within "approximately one hour", the phishing attack was stopped by Google, who advised those who had given "Google Apps" access to their email to revoke such access and change their passwords.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] In the draft of OAuth 2.1 the use of the PKCE (RFC 7636) extension for native apps has been recommended to all kinds of OAuth clients, including web applications and other confidential clients in order to prevent malicious browser extensions from performing OAuth 2.0 code injection attacks.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth framework specifies several grant types for different use cases.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Facebook's Graph API only supports OAuth 2.0.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Google supports OAuth 2.0 as the recommended authorization mechanism for all of its APIs.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Microsoft also supports OAuth 2.0 for various APIs and its Azure Active Directory service, which is used to secure many Microsoft and third party APIs.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth can be used as an authorizing mechanism to access secured RSS/Atom feeds.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Access to RSS/ATOM feeds that require authentication has always been an issue.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] For example, an RSS feed from a secured Google Site could not have been accessed using Google Reader.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Instead, three-legged OAuth would have been used to authorize that RSS client to access the feed from the Google Site.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Free software client implementations of the OAuth2 protocol such as the LibreOffice OAuth2OOo extension allows access to remote resources (ie: via the Google API or the Microsoft Graph API and OAuth 2.0) and possibly even with the LibreOffice Basic language.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] This makes it very easy to write and use HTTP requests supporting the OAuth 2.0 protocol in LibreOffice macros.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth is a service that is complementary to and distinct from OpenID.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth is unrelated to OATH, which is a reference architecture for authentication, not a standard for authorization.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] However, OAuth is directly related to OpenID Connect (OIDC), since OIDC is an authentication layer built on top of OAuth 2.0.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth is also unrelated to XACML, which is an authorization policy standard.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth can be used in conjunction with XACML, where OAuth is used for ownership consent and access delegation whereas XACML is used to define the authorization policies (e.g., managers can view documents in their region).
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth is an *authorization* protocol, rather than an *authentication* protocol.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Using OAuth on its own as an authentication method may be referred to as pseudo-authentication.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] The following diagrams highlight the differences between using OpenID (specifically designed as an authentication protocol) and OAuth for authorization.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] The site sees that the user is not authenticated.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] It formulates a request for the identity provider, encodes it, and sends it to the user as part of a redirect URL.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Once the identity provider is satisfied that the user is sufficiently authenticated, it processes the application's request, formulates a response, and sends that back to the user along with a redirect URL back to the application.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] The application decodes the identity provider's response, and carries on accordingly.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] (OAuth only) The response includes an access token which the application can use to gain direct access to the identity provider's services on the user's behalf.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] The access token acts as a kind of "valet key" that the application can include with its requests to the identity provider, which prove that it has permission from the user to access those APIs.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Because the identity provider typically (but not always) authenticates the user as part of the process of granting an OAuth access token, it is tempting to view a successful OAuth access token request as an authentication method itself.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] However, because OAuth was not designed with this use case in mind, making this assumption can lead to major security flaws.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] XACML is a policy-based, attribute-based access control authorization framework.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] XACML and OAuth can be combined to deliver a more comprehensive approach to authorization.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth does not provide a policy language with which to define access control policies.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] XACML can be used for its policy language.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Where OAuth focuses on delegated access (I, the user, grant Twitter access to my Facebook wall), and identity-centric authorization, XACML takes an attribute-based approach which can consider attributes of the user, the action, the resource, and the context (who, what, where, when, how).
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] XACML provides more fine-grained access control than OAuth does.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth is limited in granularity to the coarse functionality (the scopes) exposed by the target service.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] As a result, it often makes sense to combine OAuth and XACML together where OAuth will provide the delegated access use case and consent management and XACML will provide the authorization policies that work on the applications, processes, and data.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Lastly, XACML can work transparently across multiple stacks (APIs, web SSO, ESBs, home-grown apps, databases...).
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] OAuth focuses exclusively on HTTP-based apps.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Eran Hammer resigned from his role of lead author for the OAuth 2.0 project, withdrew from the IETF working group, and removed his name from the specification in July 2012.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Hammer cited a conflict between web and enterprise cultures as his reason for leaving, noting that IETF is a community that is "all about enterprise use cases" and "not capable of simple".
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] "What is now offered is a blueprint for an authorization protocol", he noted, "that is the enterprise way", providing a "whole new frontier to sell consulting services and integration solutions".
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] In comparing OAuth 2.0 with OAuth 1.0, Hammer points out that it has become "more complex, less interoperable, less useful, more incomplete, and most importantly, less secure".
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] He explains how architectural changes for 2.0 unbound tokens from clients, removed all signatures and cryptography at a protocol level and added expiring tokens (because tokens could not be revoked) while complicating the processing of authorization.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] David Recordon later also removed his name from the specifications for unspecified reasons.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] Dick Hardt took over the editor role, and the framework was published in October 2012.
[src:api-gateway-security/oauth] David Harris, author of the email client Pegasus Mail, has criticised OAuth 2.0 as "an absolute dog's breakfast", requiring developers to write custom modules specific to each service (Gmail, Microsoft Mail services, etc.), and to register specifically with them.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] In computer networks, **rate limiting** is used to control the rate of requests sent or received by a network interface controller.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] It can be used to prevent DoS attacks and limit web scraping.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] Research indicates flooding rates for one zombie machine are in excess of 20 HTTP GET requests per second, legitimate rates much less.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] Rate limiting should be used along with throttling pattern to minimize the number of throttling errors.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] Hardware appliances can limit the rate of requests on layer 4 or 5 of the OSI model.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] Rate limiting can be induced by the network protocol stack of the sender due to a received ECN-marked packet and also by the network scheduler of any router along the way.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] While a hardware appliance can limit the rate for a given range of IP-addresses on layer 4, it risks blocking a network with many users which are masked by NAT with a single IP address of an ISP.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] Deep packet inspection can be used to filter on the session layer but will effectively disarm encryption protocols like TLS and SSL between the appliance and the protocol server (i.e. web server).
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] Protocol servers using a request / response model, such as FTP servers or typically Web servers may use a central in-memory key-value database, like Redis or Aerospike, for session management.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] A rate limiting algorithm is used to check if the user session (or IP address) has to be limited based on the information in the session cache.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] In case a client made too many requests within a given time frame, HTTP servers can respond with status code 429: Too Many Requests.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] However, in some cases (i.e. web servers) the session management and rate limiting algorithm should be built into the application (used for dynamic content) running on the web server, rather than the web server itself.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] When a protocol server or a network device notice that the configured request limit is reached, then it will offload new requests and not respond to them.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] Sometimes they may be added to a queue to be processed once the input rate reaches an acceptable level, but at peak times the request rate can even exceed the capacities of such queues and requests have to be thrown away.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] Data centers widely use rate limiting to control the share of resources given to different tenants and applications according to their service level agreement.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] A variety of rate limiting techniques are applied in data centers using software and hardware.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] Virtualized data centers may also apply rate limiting at the hypervisor layer.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] Two important performance metrics of rate limiters in data centers are resource footprint (memory and CPU usage) which determines scalability, and precision.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] There usually exists a trade-off, that is, higher precision can be achieved by dedicating more resources to the rate limiters.
[src:api-gateway-security/rate-limiting] A considerable body of research with focus on improving performance of rate limiting in data centers.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:api-gateway-security/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] Along the ease of API integSeemadifficulties of ensuring proper authentication (AuthN) and authorization (AuthZ).
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] In a multitenant environment, security controls based on proper AuthN and AuthZ can help ensure that API access is limited to those who need (and are entitled to) it.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] Appropriate AuthN schemes enable producers (APIs or services) to properly identify consumers (clients or calling programs), and to evaluate their access level (AuthZ).
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] In other words, may a consumer invoke a particular method (business logic) based on the credentials presented?
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] Dynamic tokens: These are time based tokens obtained by caller from an authentication service.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] User-delegated tokens: These are tokens such as OAuth which are granted based on user authentication.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] Policy & attribute-based access control: policies use attributes to define how APIs can be invoked using standards such as ALFA or XACML.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] The above methods provide different level of security and ease of integration.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] Oftentimes, the easiest method of integration also offers weakest security model.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] In static strings method, the API caller or client embeds a string as a token in the request.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] This method is often referred as basic authentication.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] "From a security point of view, basic authentication is not very satisfactory.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] It means sending the user's password over the network in clear text for every single page accessed (unless a secure lower-level protocol, like SSL, is used to encrypt all transactions).
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] When an API is protected by a dynamic token, there is a time-based nonce inserted into the token.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] The token has a time to live (TTL) after which the client must acquire a new token.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] The API method has a time check algorithm, and if the token is expired, the request is forbidden.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] "An example of such token is JSON Web Token.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] This type of token is used in three-legged systems where an application needs to access an API on behalf of a user.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] Instead of revealing user id and password to the application, a user grants a token which encapsulates users permission for the application to invoke the API.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] In this approach, there is a Policy Enforcement Point either within the API itself, in the API framework (as an interceptor or message handler), or as an API gateway (e.g.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] WSO2, Kong, Tyk, or similar) that intercepts the call to the API and / or the response back from the API.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] It converts it into an authorization request (typically in XACML) which it sends to a Policy Decision Point (PDP).
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] The Policy Decision Point is configured with policies that implement dynamic access control that can use any number of user, resource, action, and context attributes to define which access is allowed or denied.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] 4. a relationship (e.g. the customer to whom the account belongs).
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] Policies are expressed in ALFA or XACML.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] As the use of Web APIs continues to grow, the landscape of threats and security practices evolves.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] In recent years, Web API security has faced new challenges and introduced advanced techniques to mitigate risks.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] In AI factories, API security is fundamental for protecting data integrity, managing access rights, and preventing malicious exploitation of interconnected systems.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] Robust strategies incorporate strong authentication (such as dynamic tokens), fine-grained authorization using policy-based controls, and continuous monitoring to safeguard against threats like data theft, model tampering, and service disruptions.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] Ensuring that APIs are visible, tracked, and properly secured at every stage—from data ingestion to inference—helps maintain the integrity of machine learning processes and model outputs.
[src:api-gateway-security/web-api-security] By aligning security measures with established methods (e.g., token-based or attribute-based access control), organizations can better protect both AI operations and sensitive assets in dynamic, multicloud, and hybrid environments.
